The '''tufted jay''' ('''''Cyanocorax dickeyi'''''), also known as the '''painted jay''' and '''Dickey's jay''', is a species of [[bird]] in the crow family [[Corvidae]]. It is [[endemic]] to a small area of the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]] in the Mexican states of [[Sinaloa]], [[Durango]], and [[Nayarit]]. A distinctive large jay, it has a prominent dark [[crest (feathers)|crest]] on its head; purplish blue back, wings, and face; a white spot above the eye and on the cheek; white undersides; and a partially white tail. Its typical [[bird vocalization|call]] is a quick, four-note vocalization.

The relationship between the tufted jay and other members of the genus ''[[Cyanocorax]]'' has been a subject of interest since the species was first described in 1935. Because of the visual similarities between the tufted jay and the [[white-tailed jay]], the two were thought by some to be closely related. A 2010 [[mitochondrial DNA]] study has shown that the tufted jay is most closely related to a group of South American jays, despite their [[Species distribution|ranges]] being separated by over {{cvt|2000|km|mi}}. They are likely descended from an ancestral jay which ranged throughout Central and South America.

The tufted jay lives in [[Sierra Madre Occidental pine–oak forests|pine-oak forests]], often remaining high in the [[canopy (biology)|canopy]]. Its diet consists primarily of [[frugivore|berries and fruit]], and to a lesser extent insects such as [[katydid]]s. It forms social [[Flock (birds)|flocks]] centred around a single [[breeding pair]], with some flocks remaining together over several generations. The tufted jay's breeding season starts in late March, with a [[clutch (eggs)|clutch]] of two to five eggs being laid in a [[nest]] that is cooperatively built by members of the flock. The tufted jay is considered [[near threatened]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN). Its population is decreasing, with an estimated 10,000–20,000 mature individuals in the wild. The primary threat to its survival is habitat destruction due to [[agricultural expansion]] and [[Deforestation in Mexico|deforestation]] due to logging and narcotic cultivation.

==Taxonomy and systematics==
The tufted jay, also known as the painted jay or Dickey's jay,{{sfnp|Haemig|1979|p=81}}{{sfnp|Lepage}} was first described by the ornithologist [[Robert Thomas Moore]] in 1935 based on [[Type (biology)|specimens]] collected on November 7, 1934, near [[Santa Lucía, Sinaloa]], in Mexico. Due to its very limited range, the species was not discovered during previous collection expeditions, despite them passing within {{cvt|56|km|mi}} of its habitat. Moore placed it in the genus ''[[Cyanocorax]]'' and gave it the [[binomial nomenclature|species name]] ''Cyanocorax dickeyi'', with the [[specific name]] being in honour of the ornithologist [[Donald Ryder Dickey]]. The tufted jay has [[Monotypic taxon|no recognized subspecies]].{{sfnp|Moore|1935|pp=274–275}}

[[File:Cyanocorax mystacalis 189151363.jpg|thumb|right|The [[white-tailed jay]] (pictured) and the tufted jay have been incorrectly considered the same species by some ornithologists.|alt=A white-tailed jay with white spots above and below eyes and a purplish blue back]]

In his initial description of the tufted jay, Moore noted that its geographically closest relative in the genus ''Cyanocorax'' was found in Costa Rica, but that it most closely resembled the [[white-tailed jay]] found in Ecuador over {{cvt|4800|km|mi}} away.{{sfnp|Moore|1935|p=277}} This indicated that the tufted jay and white-tailed jay descended from a common ancestor that once lived throughout Central and South America.{{sfnp|Amadon|1944|p=9}} This is a commonly held theory by others who have studied the tufted jay.{{sfnp|Haemig|1979|p=82}}{{sfnp|Haffer|1975|p=146}} The ornithologist [[Dean Amadon]] proposed that the tufted jay was most closely related to its geographically closest relative, the [[black-chested jay]] of Costa Rica, and that its similarity to the white-tailed jay was the result of [[convergent evolution]].{{sfnp|Amadon|1944|p=9}}

These similarities led some researchers to hypothesize that the two must be more closely related than their ranges would suggest. In 1969, the ornithologist John William Hardy discussed a theory that the tufted jay had descended from a flock of white-tailed jays that had [[Vagrancy (biology)|accidentally]] been brought to Mexico by a storm, noting that a similar phenomenon happened to a group of [[San Blas jay]]s in 1937.{{sfnp|Hardy|1969|p=364}} In 1979, ornithologist Paul Haemig elaborated on a hypothesis by [[Jean Théodore Delacour]], published in 1944, that the two jays were actually the same species.{{sfnp|Amadon|1944|p=9}}{{sfnp|Haemig|1979|pp=82–84}} Haemig said that the colouration differences between the two jays could be explained by [[Gloger's rule]], and that crest size was a "very plastic character in jays" and was of little significance when determining if the two were the same species.{{sfnp|Haemig|1979|p=81}} He proposed that the white-tailed jay had been brought to Mexico by trade between [[Pre-Columbian era|pre-Columbian]] societies, and that the tufted jay was descended from that population.{{sfnp|Haemig|1979|pp=81, 86}} A 1989 study of the [[Morphology (biology)|morphological]] characteristics of the two species seemed to support these hypotheses by proposing that the two were [[Sister group|sister species]].{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Systematics}} In 2010, a [[mitochondrial DNA]] study of the genus ''Cyanocorax'' demonstrated that the tufted jay and white-tailed jay were not sister species,{{sfnp|Bonaccorso|Peterson|Navarro-Sigüenza|Fleischer|2010|p=897}} and that the tufted jay is sister to a clade (a group of species with a common ancestor) formed by the [[white-naped jay|white-naped]], [[cayenne jay|Cayenne]], [[plush-crested jay|plush-crested]], [[azure-naped jay|azure-naped]], and [[black-chested jay]]s, all of which are found in South America.{{sfnp|Bonaccorso|Peterson|Navarro-Sigüenza|Fleischer|2010|p=905}} This study concluded that the most likely explanation for the geographical gap between the tufted jay and its South American relatives was a widely distributed common ancestor.{{sfnp|Bonaccorso|Peterson|Navarro-Sigüenza|Fleischer|2010|p=905}}

