==Description==
[[File:Tufted jay back.jpg|thumb|Tufted jays have purplish blue backs and wings.|alt=A tufted jay seen from the back, with its purplish blue back visible]]

The tufted jay is a distinctive bird within its range. It has a crest of black feathers on its head, fading to dark blue at the base. Its face is mostly black to dark blue with white spots above the eyes and white cheeks. It has a white nape and belly. The back and wings are a purplish blue which extends partway down the tail, transitioning to white about halfway down. The [[beak]] and legs are both black, and it has bright yellow [[iris (anatomy)|irises]]. Immature birds have shorter crests, lack the white spot above their eyes, and have bright blue cheeks and brown irises.{{sfnp|Goodwin|Gillmor|1976|p=297}} This [[plumage]] remains until the [[moulting|moult]] which occurs in their second year.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure}} The base of their beak is flesh-coloured, but this fades to black a few months after hatching.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|p=17}} There is no difference in plumage or colouration between males and females.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Identification}} The tufted jay's flight is described as "buoyant", and it constantly flaps its wings during [[bird flight|flight]].{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Behavior}} The average life span of a tufted jay is not known.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Demography and Populations}}

[[File:Tufted jay in flight.jpg|thumb|right|Tufted jay in flight|alt=See caption]]

The tufted jay is a large jay, measuring between {{cvt|35.5–38|cm|in}}, and with males being [[sexual dimorphism|slightly larger]] than females. A 1935 study found that the males had an average wing length of {{cvt|180.4|mm|in}}, an average tail length of {{cvt|171.3|mm|in}}, an average beak length of {{cvt|23.5|mm|in}}, and an average [[Bird feet and legs|tarsus]] length of {{cvt|45.3|mm|in}}. Females had an average wing length of {{cvt|177.1|mm|in}}, an average tail length of {{cvt|164.2|mm|in}}, an average beak length of {{cvt|23.2|mm|in}}, and an average tarsus length of {{cvt|45.9|mm|in}}.{{sfnp|Moore|1935|p=276}} The tufted jay weighs on average {{cvt|181|g|oz}}, although it is unknown if this varies between sexes.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Plumages, Molts, and Structure}}

The tufted jay somewhat visually similar to the [[black-throated magpie-jay]], although the magpie-jay is bluer, has a larger crest, and a significantly longer tail. It is also overall more bright in colouration than the tufted jay. The tufted jay is also similar to the [[white-tailed jay]], although their ranges do not overlap. Compared to the white-tailed jay, the tufted jay has a larger crest, no white on its outer wings, and more white on its tail.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Identification}}

===Vocalizations===
{{Birdsong|species=the tufted jay|url=https://xeno-canto.org/species/Cyanocorax-dickeyi}}

The tufted jay has several calls, with the most common being a rapid, four-note call transcribed as either ''rak'', ''chuck'', ''chen'', or ''ca''. This call is made by flock members when feeding and by nesting females, and a higher-pitched variation is used as a [[Mobbing (animal behavior)|mobbing]] call. When perched next to other tufted jays, individuals may make a nasal ''aaagh'' call. When guarding a nest, males make a ''tuk'' or ''tst'' call. The tufted jay is also known to mimic the calls of the [[blue mockingbird]] and the [[great-tailed grackle]].{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Sounds and Vocal Behavior}}

Prior to [[Bird#Breeding|copulation]], [[breeding pair]]s of tufted jays make a duet call. This call is described as a ''chering-chering'' followed by a metallic ''bring''. One member of the pair begins the call and it is immediately repeated by the other. These duets are repeated roughly every 20 seconds, with a soft call described as a "whisper" interspersed between repetitions. It is not certain whether the male or female begins the call. These duets last roughly 12 minutes.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|pp=34–35}}

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:Oak tree in the middle of a pine forest.jpg|thumb|right|The tufted jay can be found in pine-oak forests within [[Sierra Madre Occidental]].|alt=An epiphyte-covered oak tree surrounded by pine trees]]

The tufted jay is [[endemic]] to Mexico and is only found in a limited range within the [[Sierra Madre Occidental]], in an area of roughly {{cvt|193x32|km|mi}}.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|p=6}}{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Distribution}} Within this mountain range, they can be found in eastern [[Sinaloa]], western [[Durango]], and northern [[Nayarit]].{{sfnp|Miller|Friedmann|Griscom|Moore|1957|p=128}} This species is most often found at elevations of {{cvt|1500–2000|m|ft}}, but has been found as low as {{cvt|1200|m|ft}} and as high as {{cvt|2500|m|ft}}.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Distribution}}{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|p=6}}

The tufted jay inhabits forests throughout its range. During the non-breeding season, they are more common in higher elevation [[Sierra Madre Occidental pine–oak forests|pine-oak forests]]. In the breeding season, they can commonly be found in ravines near water sources.{{sfnp|Goodwin|Gillmor|1976|p=297}}  They can sometimes be found at higher elevations into the [[Mexican Plateau]] or areas where [[logging]] has occurred. Tufted jays are almost always near tree-tops and within the forest [[canopy (biology)|canopy]], and are rarely seen on the ground.{{sfnp|BirdLife International|2024|loc=Ecology}}

==Behaviour and ecology==
===Feeding===
[[File:Tufted jay feeding.jpg|thumb|right|A tufted jay eating an acorn|alt=See caption]]

Tufted jays eat fruits, acorns, and [[arthropod]]s. The bulk of their diet, roughly 70%, consists of plant matter, including blackberries, nuts, acorns, and the fruit from ''[[Peltostigma]]'' plants. The remaining 30% of their diet is composed of [[katydid]]s, beetles, wasps, and [[insectivore|other insects]]. Tufted jays have been observed [[egg predation|eating eggs]] which have been stolen from other birds' nests.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|pp=20–27}}{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Diet and Foraging}}

Tufted jays [[Foraging|forage]] for food in [[Flock (birds)|flocks]] during the non-breeding season, breaking up into smaller foraging groups in late March as the breeding season begins.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|p=23}} They use a variety of methods to access food; they will often perch on a branch and pry, pull, or hammer at food sources. In circumstances where a branch cannot support their weight, they hang from a higher branch and reach down, or they may briefly hover in front of the food source to access it.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|p=21}} They also [[caching|cache]] food, and will sometimes forage through [[plant litter]] on the ground.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Behavior}}{{sfnp|Lammertink|Rojas-Tomé|Casillas-Orona|Otto|1996|pp=51–52}}

During the breeding season, flocks work cooperatively to feed the nesting female. Flock members make frequent trips from their foraging area back to the nest. Nesting females may make a begging call and flap their wings when food is brought to them.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|pp=53–56}}

===Socialization and territoriality===
[[File:Tufted jay flock.jpg|thumb|right|Flock of tufted jays|alt=Three tufted jays on a branch]]

The tufted jay is a social bird, living in flocks of 4–16 individuals. The size of the flock will change throughout the year, being larger during the non-breeding season and smaller during breeding. Flocks typically consist of a single breeding pair, other secondary adults, and several juvenile birds.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|pp=15–19}} Juvenile males who disperse from the flock do so at around 13–18 months of age.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Breeding}} Groups of tufted jays stay together over the course of a year, and some last over a number of generations. Different flocks tend to be situated near to each other, but have [[Territory (animal)|territories]] which do not often overlap. When territoriality does occur, it is typically centered on areas used for breeding and foraging.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Behavior}}

The tufted jay has also shown limited hostility towards other species. Groups of Steller's jays sometimes follow tufted jay flocks, with the two species ignoring each other, although a tufted jay may dive at a Steller's jay if it approaches a nest site or while the tufted jay is foraging.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|pp=28–29}} Conversely, other species such as [[white-eared hummingbird]]s and [[Aztec thrush]]es have been observed mobbing tufted jays.{{sfnp|Moore|1938|p=234}}

===Breeding and nesting===
The breeding season for tufted jays starts in late March, and each flock contains only a single breeding pair. [[Nest]]s are built cooperatively by the breeding female, second-year juveniles, and other females in the flock.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|pp=37-46}} They are built {{cvt|5–15|m|ft}} high in trees and are approximately {{cvt|41|cm|in}} in diameter and {{cvt|6|cm|in}} deep. The nest is made of sticks, with the nest cup consisting of roots and smaller branches. Females will sit in the nest even prior to any eggs being laid.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|pp=37-46}}

Eggs are laid in April or May, with the [[clutch (eggs)|clutch]] averaging two to five eggs.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Breeding}} They are an olive colour with brown speckles, and measure {{cvt|36–38|mm|in}} long and {{cvt|24–25.4|mm|in}} wide.{{sfnp|Moore|1938|p=237}} Only the female will [[Egg incubation|incubate]] the eggs, while the male and other members of the flock provide food for the nesting female. The incubation period lasts 18–19 days, and hatchlings remain in the nest for roughly 24 days.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Breeding}} Hatchlings are [[altricial]] (immature and helpless at birth) and born without feathers.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|p=62}} The cooperative feeding of the nesting female extends to the hatchlings, with the flock passing food to the nesting female, who then passes it to the hatchlings.{{sfnp|Crossin|1965|pp=63–64}} It is not known at what age tufted jays start breeding.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Demography and Populations}}

==Conservation and status==
[[File:Cyanocorax dickeyi 271212171.jpg|thumb|A flock of tufted jays foraging next to a road|alt=A group of eight tufted jays on the ground beside a winding road]]

The tufted jay is listed as [[near threatened]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN). As of 2020, their population is considered to be decreasing, with 10,000–20,000 mature individuals. Since the population of the tufted jay is relatively restricted geographically, the primary threats to its survival are [[habitat destruction]] due to agricultural expansion, deforestation from logging and the cultivation of [[narcotic]]s, and [[forest fire]]s. [[Habitat fragmentation]] caused by road construction is also thought to pose a threat. The tufted jay is known to be hunted or killed by humans, such as those involved in narcotic cultivation or children. Drought also presents a threat to the tufted jay as it results in a lack of food sources. [[Climate change]] is likely to result in future prolonged droughts, which could cause a significant decrease in the tufted jay's population. Some water sources used by groups of tufted jays have also been destroyed by human activity.{{sfnp|BirdLife International|2020}}

While there are no active conservation plans in place for the tufted jay,{{sfnp|BirdLife International|2020}} they are considered endangered by the Mexican government, and at great risk of extinction by [[Partners in Flight]].{{sfnp|Escalante|Nequiz|2004|p=179}}{{sfnp|Berlanga|Kennedy|Rich|Arizmendi|2010|p=38}} Since 2004, the El Palmito ''[[ejido]]'' in Sinaloa has a community conservation plan in place. A large number of tufted jays are found near here, and the conservation plan aims to encourage ecotourism and education while limiting logging activities.{{sfnp|Kittelson|Ghalambor|2020|loc=Conservation and Management}}

